Reasoning: The paper deals with logic-based approaches to complexity theory and implicit computational complexity, which are topics typically covered in the cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) sub-category. The use of geometric characterisations also suggests a possible connection to the cs.CC (Computational Complexity) sub-category. The mention of measure-preserving maps and the study of complexity classes without reference to specific machine models suggests a possible connection to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. The use of automata and graphs suggests a possible connection to the cs.FL (Formal Languages and Automata Theory) sub-category. Finally, the mention of linear logic suggests a possible connection to the cs.PL (Programming Languages) sub-category.
